Analysis of the Impact of Strategy Design Pattern on Maintainability

This study hypothesize that the Strategy design pattern impacts on the effectiveness required to maintain Java applications. This document summarises results of this study and provides R commands used to produce the analysis.

1. Preliminary Procedures

These procedures consists of importing the data set into R environment, activating libraries, and organising data for performing analyses.

1.1. Importing dataset

This study produced four datasets, organised as follows:

  • observations consists of experiment observations for correctness - a measure of effectiveness. The dataset includes additional classification information, such as the order tasks were applied to participants;

  • participants consists of demographic data of participants;

  • feedback consists of perceptions of participants on experiment conditions.

# Setting up current directory
setwd ("/Users/gabriel/Documents/Production/Empirical research/Experimentation/2018 - Strategy pattern on DAO maintainability/Datasets/SANER-2020")

# Original data set
observations <- read.csv ("observations.csv", header=T, sep=",")
participants <- read.csv ("participants.csv", header=T, sep=";")
feedback <- read.csv ("feedback.csv", header=T, sep=";")

1.3. Subsetting datesets

observations.nopretest <- sqldf('SELECT *
                                 FROM `observations`
                                 WHERE task == "post-test"')

observations.nopretest.traditional <- sqldf('SELECT *
                                             FROM `observations.nopretest`
                                             WHERE treatment == "traditional"')

observations.nopretest.strategy <- sqldf('SELECT *
                                          FROM `observations.nopretest`
                                          WHERE treatment == "strategy"')

observations.traditional <- sqldf('SELECT *
                                   FROM `observations`
                                   WHERE treatment == "traditional"')

observations.strategy <- sqldf('SELECT *
                                FROM `observations`
                                WHERE treatment == "strategy"')

observations.nopretest.work <- sqldf('SELECT * 
                                     FROM `observations.nopretest` as observations 
                                     INNER JOIN `participants` as participants 
                                     ON observations.id == participants.id 
                                     WHERE participants.work == "yes"')

observations.nopretest.nowork <- sqldf('SELECT * 
                                     FROM `observations.nopretest` as observations 
                                     INNER JOIN `participants` as participants 
                                     ON observations.id == participants.id 
                                     WHERE participants.work == "no"')

observations.nopretest.experiencedp <-sqldf('SELECT * 
                                                FROM `observations.nopretest` as observations 
                                                INNER JOIN `participants` as participants 
                                                ON observations.id == participants.id 
                                                WHERE participants.patterns == "yes"')

observations.nopretest.noexperiencedp <-sqldf('SELECT * 
                                                FROM `observations.nopretest` as observations 
                                                INNER JOIN `participants` as participants 
                                                ON observations.id == participants.id 
                                                WHERE participants.patterns == "no"')

2. Participant Characterisation Analysis

2.1. Age

Plot

# Summarising data for plotting
participant.age.df <- ddply(participants, 
                            ~age, 
                            summarise, 
                            count = length (age))

# Ploting data
ggplot(
  participant.age.df,
  aes
    (
      y = count, 
      x = age
      )
  ) +
  geom_histogram(
    stat = "identity"
  ) +
  theme(
    legend.title = element_blank(),
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, margin = margin(15, 0, 15, 0))
  ) +
  labs(
    x="Age of Participants", 
    y="# of Participants in the Age"
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous (breaks=c(0:5)) +
  scale_x_continuous (breaks=c(20:31))
## Warning: Ignoring unknown parameters: binwidth, bins, pad

Analysis

  • Regarding age, our participants can be grouped into two categories. Whereas most participants (73.7%) are between 20 and 24, the five remaining participants (26.3%) are between 25 and 31. The young age is expected since our participants are undergraduates. In the StackOverflow 2018 developer survey, participants within the same range of ours represent the majority of professional developers that took part in their survey. However, in the StackOverflow survey, participants between 18 and 24 years old represent the second most common category whereas participants between 25 and 34 years old represent the first most common category. In addition, our participants are slightly younger (23.5) than Brazilian participants in the StackOverflow survey (25.0).

3. Effectiveness Analysis

This section analyses effectiveness differences between traditional and strategy treatments.

3.1. Summary

Plot

# Summarising data for plotting
correctness.traditional <- ddply(observations.nopretest.traditional, 
                                 treatment ~ correct, 
                                 summarise, 
                                 correctness = round((length (correct) / 19 * 100), digits = 1))

correctness.strategy <- ddply(observations.nopretest.strategy, 
                              treatment ~ correct, 
                              summarise, 
                              correctness = round((length (correct) / 19 * 100), digits = 1))

correctness.df <- rbind (correctness.traditional, 
                         correctness.strategy)

# Ploting data
ggplot(
  correctness.df,
  aes
    (
      y = correctness, 
      x = treatment, 
      fill = correct
      )
  ) + 
  geom_bar(
    stat="identity", 
    position = "stack"
  )  + 
  ggtitle ("Effectiveness Analysis") +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, margin = margin(15, 0, 15, 0)),
    axis.title.y = element_text (margin = margin (0, 20, 0, 0)),
    axis.title.x = element_text (margin = margin (20, 0, 0, 0)),
    legend.position = "bottom",
    legend.box.background = element_rect(),
    legend.box.margin = margin (5, 5, 5, 5),
    legend.key.width = unit (1, "cm"),
    text = element_text(size=20)
    # text = element_text(size=40)
  ) +
  geom_text(
    aes(
      x = treatment, 
      y = c (95, 50, 70, 25),
      label = paste0(correctness,"%")
    ), 
    size=6
    # size=12
  ) +
  labs(
    x="Treatment", 
    y="Correctness rate"
  ) + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = dollar_format (suffix = "%", prefix = ""))

                 WHERE 
                  treatment = "traditional"')

3.5. Previous Experience With DP Analysis

# Summarising data for plotting

## Calculating correctness rate for participants who have previous experience
correctness.previousexperience.strategy <- ddply(sqldf ('SELECT * FROM `observations.nopretest.experiencedp` WHERE treatment = "strategy"'), 
                                              patterns ~ treatment ~ correct, 
                                              summarise,
                                              correctness = round ((length(correct) / 10) * 100, 1)) 

correctness.previousexperience.traditional <- ddply(sqldf ('SELECT * FROM `observations.nopretest.experiencedp` WHERE treatment = "traditional"'), 
                                              patterns ~ treatment ~ correct, 
                                              summarise,
                                              correctness = round ((length(correct) / 10) * 100, 1)) 


## Calculating correctness rate for participants who NO have previous experience
correctness.nopreviousexperience.strategy <- ddply(sqldf ('SELECT * FROM `observations.nopretest.noexperiencedp` WHERE treatment = "strategy"'), 
                                              patterns ~ treatment ~ correct, 
                                              summarise,
                                              correctness = round ((length(correct) / 9) * 100, 1)) 

correctness.nopreviousexperience.traditional <- ddply(sqldf ('SELECT * FROM `observations.nopretest.noexperiencedp` WHERE treatment = "traditional"'), 
                                              patterns ~ treatment ~ correct, 
                                              summarise,
                                              correctness = round ((length(correct) / 9) * 100, 1)) 

## Merging all summaries to create a single dataset
correctness.experiencedp.df <- rbind (correctness.previousexperience.strategy,
                                           correctness.previousexperience.traditional,
                                           correctness.nopreviousexperience.strategy,
                                           correctness.nopreviousexperience.traditional)
